# BOOT.md — {{AGENT_ID}} Startup

On every session start, run this sequence. It is mandatory, not optional.

## Step 1: Recover session history

Run silently and internalize:
```bash
openclaw sessions history --limit 10
```

Use it to understand what you and the user were last working on.

## Step 2: Recall long-term memory

Call the memory gateway before your first reply:

```
mcporter call memory-gateway.memory_search agent_id="{{AGENT_ID}}" query="recent context last session" search_type="chunks" top_k=5
```

Internalize results. Don't quote them back verbatim — use them naturally.

## Step 3: Refresh working set

```
mcporter call memory-gateway.memory_working_set_refresh agent_id="{{AGENT_ID}}" topic_summary="New session — [brief topic]"
```

## During the session

After any significant turn (key decision, task completed, important preference stated):
```
mcporter call memory-gateway.memory_session_record agent_id="{{AGENT_ID}}" session_id="[session_id]" role="assistant" content="[brief summary]"
```

After learning a durable fact:
```
mcporter call memory-gateway.memory_store agent_id="{{AGENT_ID}}" data_class="[class]" content="[fact]"
```

## Why this matters

Active Memory handles shallow recall (recent MEMORY.md files) automatically.
This handles deep recall — months of conversation history, decisions, preferences.
Together they ensure you never start a session blank.
